 stricter, and<br />gcc ends up having (a) more wide coverage and (b) doesn't have the<br />bugs clang has.<br /><br />Honestly, I think the clang "version 14 or more" check is simply<br />buggy. We *know* that check fails. Don't do it.<br /><br />Make it "strictly more than 14.0.0" which hopefully doesn't fail, is<br />cheap and easy, and which will make clang work correctly in the not<br />too distant future.<br /><br />In the meantime, we have the gcc checks,  and we'll have a release<br />without pointless warnings from garbage clang versions.<br /><br />                Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
